[Patient] How much water should I drink daily to manage my heart failure?
[Educator] Aim for about 8-10 cups of fluid per day, but consult with your healthcare provider.

[Patient] I'm worried about drinking too much water. What should I do?
[Educator] Monitor your fluid intake and watch for swelling or sudden weight gain.

[Patient] Can I drink other fluids besides water?
[Educator] Yes, you can also drink low-sodium broths, herbal teas, or unsweetened juices.

[Patient] Should I limit my caffeine intake?
[Educator] Yes, limit caffeine as it can affect your heart. Try decaf or herbal teas.

[Patient] Are there any fruits or vegetables that can help with fluid intake?
[Educator] Water-rich fruits like watermelon, oranges, and cucumbers can help with hydration.

[Patient] How can I remember to drink enough fluids throughout the day?
[Educator] Set reminders on your phone or keep a water bottle with you at all times.

[Patient] What about alcohol, should I avoid it?
[Educator] Limit alcohol intake as it can worsen heart failure symptoms. Drink in moderation.

[Patient] I sweat a lot when I exercise, do I need to drink more water?
[Educator] Yes, increase your fluid intake when you sweat more to stay hydrated.

[Patient] How can I tell if I'm drinking too much or too little fluids?
[Educator] Pay attention to your body. If you feel thirsty, drink more. If you have swelling, reduce intake.

[Patient] Can drinking too much water harm my heart?
[Educator] Yes, excessive fluid intake can strain your heart. Stick to the recommended amount.